title: For Sale:  The Legal Aspects of Carrying a Concealed Weapon And the Use of Deadly Force in Self-Defense
postcontent:
Event Details

When can you use force to stop an attack? What kind of force can you use and when?  Under what circumstances are deadly force justified, and when does the law require you to use a lesser degree of force?

This course has been requested by many students due to current events, and it is designed for those people concerned about learning Colorado Self-Defense Laws. In recent times the news has carried stories about individuals using deadly force in self-defense. Some have been acquitted, and some have been convicted. Although these cases have arisen in other states, you need to know the law in Colorado, so hopefully you will not be subjected to civil and/or criminal litigation with its accompanying costs and consequences.

The Deadly Force for Self-Defense information is difficult to find and understand, and although nobody, including us, can give you a guarantee that you will do everything correctly and avoid trouble, we can help you navigate the laws for a more clear understanding, so you can better appreciate the issues involved.

This is a great seminar for the Concealed Carry Permit Holder; but is also very important for those concerned with self-defense in general.  Whether you have a firearm for home defense, defense during travel, or at work.... this seminar can help you prepare for the worst.

Included in the Seminar will be discussion on the Use of Force Continuum, Disparity of Force, and the Colorado "Make my Day" law.  There will be a Q & A session with Mr. Barry Meinster & Mr. John Duran where you can ask the tough questions and get informative answers.  There will be discussion and handouts on environmental awareness, combat mindset, and the moral/eithical question of using Lethal Force to stop an attacker.  There is a real valuable wealth of information in this course that you will not see in other courses offered in Colorado.

There is ample parking and seating for 25.  You must purchase a ticket to reserve your seat in advance.  Seating is first come first served.  Drinks and snacks will be provided and there are scheduled breaks during the seminar.

The cost for this informative training is $75 per attendee and seating is limited, so please make your reservations early by purchasing tickets through this online flier.

For further questions please call John Duran at REDACTED or email REDACTED

Link for Tickets:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/the-legal-aspects-of-carrying-a-concealed-weapon-and-the-use-of-deadly-force-in-self-defense-tickets-REDACTED9

title: For Sale:  Ka-Bar/ Becker BK-7
location: Harris Co./ N. Columbus, Columbus, GA, Georgia
postcontent:
I'm selling a nearly new BK-7 survival/bushcraft knife that I rarely use, and am just thinning the herd.
The BK-series knives are very high quality and highly popular. They're made by Ka-Bar in the USA, out of 1095 cro-van high carbon steel, with full tang, and based on designs by Ethan Becker. The BK-7 is surprisingly light and well balanced for a large knife.
I only used it last winter, sitting on the living room floor splitting some small pieces of cedar into really thin pieces, for kindling.  Cedar is very soft, so I just used the heel of my hand to tap the spine of the blade and push the knife through the wood pieces, no hammering on the spine with a log or anything. There are some very light marks on either side of the blade, but not even close to breaking through the finish on the knife, they're very superficial.
 Other than that, the knife and sheath are pristine, is very sharp and still has the factory edge. 
I had my brother take a photo and e-mail it to me, but it's too dark and looks like crap, so I'm just posting a couple off the web.
Asking $60,firm, which is less than I paid a year or two ago. Last I checked, they were running $80+.
Thanks for looking........

title: For Sale:  .22 Shooters Wanted: Smallbore Rimfire Competition
location: Palomino Valley / Pyramid Lake, Reno, Nevada
postcontent:
Palomino Valley Gun Club is hosting smallbore rimfire silhouette matches at the Regional Shooting Facility located near near Pyramid Lake in Reno, Nevada.

The PVGC smallbore silhouette match is designed for all shooter skill levels, and features NRA hunter pistol targets engaged at four separate distances. This match is for rimfire rifle or pistol equipment, with classes limited to Metallic sight unsupported, Telescopic (magnified) sight unsupported, and open sight supported classes. This match will teach shooters firearm safety, range etiquette, and basic marksmanship skills. The course of fire will be challenging enough to promote growth, and enable graduation into other disciplines. 

Participation is FREE for all junior shooters, $5 adult members, $10 adult non-members.

2014 Match Schedule:
Saturday 8/30 (FREE to ALL juniors)
Sunday 9/21 (FREE to ALL juniors)
Sunday 11/2 (FREE to ALL juniors)

Shooters must be present at the covered Smallbore Range for the 9AM safety briefing to participate. Arrive as early as 8AM to enjoy some practice shooting before the match.

Contact Olin Coles for details: REDACTED REDACTED

Match details are available here: http://palominogunclub.org/262/smallbore-silhouette-match-description/

Course of Fire Details
String #1: fire ten rounds in five minutes at chicken targets 40m/44y away using a standing position.
Short break to score and reset targets
String #2: fire ten rounds in five minutes at peccary (pig) targets 60m/66y away using a sitting/kneeling position.
Short break to score and reset targets
String #3: fire ten rounds in five minutes at turkey targets 77m/84y away using a prone position.
Short break to score and reset targets
String #4: fire ten rounds in five minutes at sheep targets 100m/109y away using any position.
Short break to score and reset targets
Conduct shoot-off if necessary
Short break to clear firearms and equipment from the line
Collect targets and announce match winners.

Allowed cartridges:
.17 and .22 air gun pellet
.17 HM2 (plastic tip only)
.22 BB Cap, .22 CB Cap
.22 Short, .22 Long, .22 Long Rifle
.22 WRF

Prohibited cartridges:
.17 HMR
.22 WMR
.22 Hornet
5mm Remington Rimfire Magnum
No steel or armor piercing allowed
No tracer ammunition allowed
